data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new **span conversion rules** cause `array.Contains(num)` on `int[]` to resolve to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based method calls**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## Fix options

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` so the compiler picks the LINQ overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three force the compiler back to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains`, which is representable in expression trees. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — it now binds to the in-place `Span` version returning `void`.
